[src:guava-java-lib/java-collections-framework] The **Java collections framework** is a set of classes and interfaces that implement commonly reusable collection data structures (collections).
[src:guava-java-lib/java-collections-framework] Although referred to as a framework, it works in a manner of a library.
[src:guava-java-lib/java-collections-framework] The collections framework provides both interfaces that define various collections and classes that implement them.
[src:guava-java-lib/java-collections-framework] `Collection`s and arrays are similar in that they both hold references to objects and they can be managed as a group.
[src:guava-java-lib/java-collections-framework] However, unlike arrays, `Collection`s do not need to be assigned a certain capacity when instantiated.
[src:guava-java-lib/java-collections-framework] `Collection`s can grow and shrink in size automatically when objects are added or removed.
[src:guava-java-lib/java-collections-framework] `Collection`s cannot hold primitive data types such as `int`, `long`, or `double`.
[src:guava-java-lib/java-collections-framework] Instead, `Collection`s can hold wrapper classes such as `java.lang.Integer`, `java.lang.Long`, or `java.lang.Double`.
[src:guava-java-lib/java-collections-framework] `Collection`s are generic and hence invariant, but arrays are covariant.
[src:guava-java-lib/java-collections-framework] This can be considered an advantage of generic objects such as `Collection` when compared to arrays, because under circumstances, using the generic `Collection` instead of an array prevents run time exceptions by instead throwing a compile-time exception to inform the developer to fix the code.
[src:guava-java-lib/java-collections-framework] For example, if a developer declares an `Object[]` object, and assigns the `Object[]` object to the value returned by a new `Long[]` instance with a certain capacity, no compile-time exception will be thrown.
[src:guava-java-lib/java-collections-framework] If the developer attempts to add a `String` to this `Long[]` object, the java program will throw an `ArrayStoreException`.
[src:guava-java-lib/java-collections-framework] `Collection`s are generic and hence reified, but arrays are not reified.
[src:guava-java-lib/java-collections-framework] Collection implementations in pre-JDK 1.2 versions of the Java platform included few data structure classes, but did not contain a collections framework.
[src:guava-java-lib/java-collections-framework] The standard methods for grouping Java objects were via the array, the `Vector`, and the `Hashtable` classes, which unfortunately were not easy to extend, and did not implement a standard member interface.
[src:guava-java-lib/java-collections-framework] To address the need for reusable collection data structures, several independent frameworks were developed, the most used being Doug Lea's *Collections package*, and ObjectSpace *Generic Collection Library* (JGL), whose main goal was consistency with the C++ Standard Template Library (STL).
[src:guava-java-lib/java-collections-framework] The collections framework was designed and developed primarily by Joshua Bloch, and was introduced in JDK 1.2.
[src:guava-java-lib/java-collections-framework] It reused many ideas and classes from Doug Lea's *Collections package*, which was deprecated as a result.
[src:guava-java-lib/java-collections-framework] Sun Microsystems chose not to use the ideas of JGL, because they wanted a compact framework, and consistency with C++ was not one of their goals.
[src:guava-java-lib/java-collections-framework] Doug Lea later developed a concurrency package, comprising new Collection-related classes.
[src:guava-java-lib/java-collections-framework] An updated version of these concurrency utilities was included in JDK 5.0 as of JSR 166.
[src:guava-java-lib/java-collections-framework] Most collections in Java that are not maps are derived from the **`java.util.Collection`** interface.
[src:guava-java-lib/java-collections-framework] `Collection` defines the basic parts of all collections.
[src:guava-java-lib/java-collections-framework] The interface has the `add(E e)` and `remove(E e)` methods for adding to and removing from a `Collection` respectively.
[src:guava-java-lib/java-collections-framework] It also has the `toArray()` method, which converts the `Collection` into an array of `Object`s in the `Collection` (with return type of `Object[]`).
[src:guava-java-lib/java-collections-framework] Finally, the `contains(E e)` method checks if a specified element exists in the `Collection`.
[src:guava-java-lib/java-collections-framework] The `Collection` interface is a subinterface of **`java.lang.Iterable`**, so any `Collection` may be the target of a for-each statement.
[src:guava-java-lib/java-collections-framework] (The `Iterable` interface provides the `iterator()` method used by for-each statements.) All `Collection`s implement **`java.util.Iterator`** to scan all of the elements in the `Collection`.
[src:guava-java-lib/java-collections-framework] Any `Collection` can store any `Object`.
[src:guava-java-lib/java-collections-framework] For example, any implementation of `Collection<String>` contains `String` objects.
[src:guava-java-lib/java-collections-framework] No casting is required when using the `String` objects from an implementation of `Collection<String>`.
[src:guava-java-lib/java-collections-framework] Note that the angled brackets `< >` can hold a type argument that specifies which type the `Collection` holds.
[src:guava-java-lib/java-collections-framework] There are several kinds of collections: queues, maps, lists and sets.
[src:guava-java-lib/java-collections-framework] Queues allow the programmer to insert items in a certain order and retrieve those items in the same order.
[src:guava-java-lib/java-collections-framework] The base interfaces for queues are called `Queue`.
[src:guava-java-lib/java-collections-framework] Dictionaries/Maps store references to objects with a lookup key to access the object's values.
[src:guava-java-lib/java-collections-framework] One example of a key is an identification card.
[src:guava-java-lib/java-collections-framework] The base interface for dictionaries/maps is called `Map`.
[src:guava-java-lib/java-collections-framework] Lists are finite collections where it can store the same value multiple times.
[src:guava-java-lib/java-collections-framework] Sets are unordered collections that can be iterated and contain each element at most once.
[src:guava-java-lib/java-collections-framework] The base interface for sets is called `Set`.
[src:guava-java-lib/java-collections-framework] Lists are implemented in the collections framework via the **`java.util.List`**interface.
[src:guava-java-lib/java-collections-framework] It defines a list as essentially a more flexible version of an array.
[src:guava-java-lib/java-collections-framework] Elements have a specific order, and duplicate elements are allowed.
[src:guava-java-lib/java-collections-framework] Elements can be placed in a specific position.
[src:guava-java-lib/java-collections-framework] They can also be searched for within the list.
[src:guava-java-lib/java-collections-framework] There are several concrete classes that implement `List`, including `AbstractList` and all of its corresponding subclasses, as well as `CopyOnWriteArrayList`.
[src:guava-java-lib/java-collections-framework] The direct subclasses of `AbstractList` class include `AbstractSequentialList`, `ArrayList` and `Vector`.
[src:guava-java-lib/java-collections-framework] `AbstractList` is an example of a *skeletal implementation*, which leverages and combines the advantages of interfaces and abstract classes by making it easy for the developer to develop their own implementation for the given interface.
[src:guava-java-lib/java-collections-framework] The **`java.util.ArrayList`** class implements the `List` as an array.
[src:guava-java-lib/java-collections-framework] Whenever functions specific to a `List` are required, the class moves the elements around within the array in order to do it.
[src:guava-java-lib/java-collections-framework] The **`java.util.LinkedList`** class stores the elements in nodes that each have a pointer to the previous and next nodes in the `List`.
[src:guava-java-lib/java-collections-framework] The `List` can be traversed by following the pointers, and elements can be added or removed simply by changing the pointers around to place the node in its proper place.
[src:guava-java-lib/java-collections-framework] The `Vector` class has `Stack` as its direct subclass.
[src:guava-java-lib/java-collections-framework] This is an example of a violation of the composition over inheritance principle in the Java platform libraries, since in computer science, a vector is generally not a stack.
[src:guava-java-lib/java-collections-framework] Composition would have been more appropriate in this scenario.
[src:guava-java-lib/java-collections-framework] The `Stack` class `extends` class **`java.util.Vector`** with five operations that allow a `Vector` to be treated as a `Stack`.
[src:guava-java-lib/java-collections-framework] Stacks are created using **`java.util.Stack`**.
[src:guava-java-lib/java-collections-framework] The `Stack` offers methods to put a new object on the `Stack` (method `push(E e)`) and to get objects from the `Stack` (method `pop()`).
[src:guava-java-lib/java-collections-framework] A `Stack` returns the object according to last-in-first-out (LIFO), e.g. the object which was placed latest on the `Stack` is returned first.
[src:guava-java-lib/java-collections-framework] `java.util.Stack` is a standard implementation of a stack provided by Java.
[src:guava-java-lib/java-collections-framework] The `Stack` class represents a last-in-first-out (LIFO) stack of objects.
[src:guava-java-lib/java-collections-framework] The Stack class has five additional operations that allow a `Vector` to be treated as a `Stack`.
[src:guava-java-lib/java-collections-framework] When a `Stack` is first created, it contains no items.
[src:guava-java-lib/java-collections-framework] The `CopyOnWriteArrayList` extends the `Object` class, and does not extend any other classes.
[src:guava-java-lib/java-collections-framework] `CopyOnWriteArrayList` allows for thread-safety without performing excessive synchronization.
[src:guava-java-lib/java-collections-framework] In some scenarios, synchronization is mandatory.
[src:guava-java-lib/java-collections-framework] For example, if a method modifies a static field, and the method must be called by multiple threads, then synchronization is mandatory and concurrency utilities such as `CopyOnWriteArrayList` should not be used.
[src:guava-java-lib/java-collections-framework] However synchronization can incur a performance overhead.
[src:guava-java-lib/java-collections-framework] For scenarios where synchronization is not mandatory, then the `CopyOnWriteArrayList` is a viable, thread-safe alternative to synchronization that leverages multi-core processors and results in higher CPU utilization.
[src:guava-java-lib/java-collections-framework] The **`java.util.Queue`** interface defines the queue data structure, which stores elements in the order in which they are inserted.
[src:guava-java-lib/java-collections-framework] New additions go to the end of the line, and elements are removed from the front.
[src:guava-java-lib/java-collections-framework] This interface is implemented by `java.util.LinkedList`, **`java.util.ArrayDeque`**, and **`java.util.PriorityQueue`**.
[src:guava-java-lib/java-collections-framework] The direct subclasses of `AbstractQueue` class include `ArrayBlockingQueue`, `ConcurrentLinkedQueue`, `DelayeQueue`, `LinkedBlockingDeque`, `LinkedBlockingQueue`.
[src:guava-java-lib/java-collections-framework] `LinkedTransferQueue` and `PriorityBlockingQueue`.
[src:guava-java-lib/java-collections-framework] Note that `ArrayDeque` and `ConcurrentLinkedDeque` both extend `AbstractCollection` but do not extend any other abstract classes such as `AbstractQueue`.
[src:guava-java-lib/java-collections-framework] `AbstractQueue` is an example of a *skeletal implementation*.
[src:guava-java-lib/java-collections-framework] The `java.util.PriorityQueue` class implements `java.util.Queue`, but also alters it.
[src:guava-java-lib/java-collections-framework] `PriorityQueue` has an additional `comparator()` method.
[src:guava-java-lib/java-collections-framework] Instead of elements being ordered in the order in which they are inserted, they are ordered by priority.
[src:guava-java-lib/java-collections-framework] The method used to determine priority is either the `java.lang.Comparable#compareTo(T)` method in the elements, or a method given in the constructor.
[src:guava-java-lib/java-collections-framework] The class creates this by using a heap to keep the items sorted.
[src:guava-java-lib/java-collections-framework] The `java.util.concurrent.ConcurrentLinkedQueue` class extends `java.util.AbstractQueue`.
[src:guava-java-lib/java-collections-framework] `ConcurrentLinkedQueue` implements the `java.util.Queue` interface.
[src:guava-java-lib/java-collections-framework] The `ConcurrentLinkedQueue` class is a thread-safe collection, since for any an element placed inside a `ConcurrentLinkedQueue`, the Java Collection Library guarantees that the element is *safely published* by allowing any thread to get the element from the collection.
[src:guava-java-lib/java-collections-framework] An object is said to be *safely published* if the object's state is made visible to all other thread at the same point in time.
[src:guava-java-lib/java-collections-framework] Safe publication usually requires synchronization of the publishing and consuming threads.
[src:guava-java-lib/java-collections-framework] The **`java.util.concurrent.BlockingQueue`** interface extends `Queue`.
[src:guava-java-lib/java-collections-framework] The `BlockingQueue` interface has the following direct sub-interfaces: `BlockingDeque` and `TransferQueue`.
[src:guava-java-lib/java-collections-framework] `BlockingQueue` works like a regular `Queue`, but additions to and removals from the `BlockingQueue` are blocking.
[src:guava-java-lib/java-collections-framework] If `remove(Object o)` is called on an empty `BlockingQueue`, it can be set to wait either a specified time or indefinitely for an item to appear in the `BlockingQueue`.
[src:guava-java-lib/java-collections-framework] Similarly, adding an item using the method `add(Object o)` is subject to an optional capacity restriction on the `BlockingQueue`, and the method can wait for space to become available in the `BlockingQueue` before returning.
[src:guava-java-lib/java-collections-framework] `BlockingQueue` interface introduces a method `take()` which removes and gets the head of the `BlockingQueue`, and waits until the `BlockingQueue` is no longer empty if required.
[src:guava-java-lib/java-collections-framework] The `Deque` interface extends the `Queue` interface.
[src:guava-java-lib/java-collections-framework] While a regular `Queue` only allows insertions at the rear and removals at the front, the `Deque` allows insertions or removals to take place both at the front and the back.
[src:guava-java-lib/java-collections-framework] A `Deque` is like a `Queue` that can be used forwards or backwards, or both at once.
[src:guava-java-lib/java-collections-framework] Additionally, both a forwards and a backwards iterator can be generated.
[src:guava-java-lib/java-collections-framework] The `Deque` interface is implemented by `java.util.ArrayDeque` and `java.util.LinkedList`.
[src:guava-java-lib/java-collections-framework] `LinkedList`, of course, also implements the `List` interface and can also be used as one.
[src:guava-java-lib/java-collections-framework] `LinkedList` implements the **`java.util.Deque`** interface, giving it more flexibility.
[src:guava-java-lib/java-collections-framework] `ArrayDeque` implements the `Queue` as an array.
[src:guava-java-lib/java-collections-framework] Similar to `LinkedList`, `ArrayDeque` also implements the **`java.util.Deque`** interface.
[src:guava-java-lib/java-collections-framework] The **`java.util.concurrent.BlockingDeque`** interface extends `java.util.concurrent.BlockingQueue`.
[src:guava-java-lib/java-collections-framework] `BlockingDeque` is similar to `BlockingQueue`.
[src:guava-java-lib/java-collections-framework] It provides the same methods for insertion and removal with time limits for waiting for the insertion or removal to become possible.
[src:guava-java-lib/java-collections-framework] However, the interface also provides the flexibility of a `Deque`.
[src:guava-java-lib/java-collections-framework] Insertions and removals can take place at both ends.
[src:guava-java-lib/java-collections-framework] The blocking function is combined with the `Deque` function.
[src:guava-java-lib/java-collections-framework] Java's **`java.util.Set`**interface defines the `Set`.
[src:guava-java-lib/java-collections-framework] A `Set` can't have any duplicate elements in it.
[src:guava-java-lib/java-collections-framework] Additionally, the `Set` has no set order.
[src:guava-java-lib/java-collections-framework] As such, elements can't be found by index.
[src:guava-java-lib/java-collections-framework] `Set` is implemented by **`java.util.HashSet`**, **`java.util.LinkedHashSet`**, and **`java.util.TreeSet`**.
[src:guava-java-lib/java-collections-framework] There are several implementations of the Set interface, including `AbstractSet` and its subclasses, and the final static inner class `ConcurrentHashMap.KeySetView<K, V>` (where `K` and `V` are formal type parameters).
[src:guava-java-lib/java-collections-framework] `AbstractSet` is a *skeletal implementation* for the `Set` interface.
[src:guava-java-lib/java-collections-framework] Direct subclasses of `AbstractSet` include `ConcurrentSkipListSet`, `CopyOnWriteArraySet`, `EnumSet`, `HashSet` and `TreeSet`.
[src:guava-java-lib/java-collections-framework] The `EnumSet` class extends `AbstractSet`.
[src:guava-java-lib/java-collections-framework] The `EnumSet` class has no public constructors, and only contain static factory methods.
[src:guava-java-lib/java-collections-framework] `EnumSet` contains the static factory method `EnumSet.of()`.
[src:guava-java-lib/java-collections-framework] It takes in several parameters, takes into account of the type of the parameters, then returns an instance with the appropriate type.
[src:guava-java-lib/java-collections-framework] As of 2018, In Java SE8 OpenJDK implementation uses two implementations of `EnumSet` which are invisible to the client, which are `RegularEnumSet` and `JumboEnumSet`.
[src:guava-java-lib/java-collections-framework] If the `RegularEnumSet` no longer provided any performance benefits for small enum types, it could be removed from the library without negatively impacting the Java Collection Library.
[src:guava-java-lib/java-collections-framework] `EnumSet` is a good replacement for the *bit fields*, which is a type of set, as described below.
[src:guava-java-lib/java-collections-framework] Traditionally, whenever developers encountered elements of an enumerated type that needs to be placed in a set, the developer would use the *int enum pattern* in which every constant is assigned a different power of 2.
[src:guava-java-lib/java-collections-framework] This bit representation enables the developer to use the bitwise OR operation, so that the constants can be combined into a set, also known as a *bit field*.
[src:guava-java-lib/java-collections-framework] This *bit field representation* enables the developer to make efficient set-based operations and bitwise arithmetic such as intersection and unions.
[src:guava-java-lib/java-collections-framework] However, there are many problems with *bit field representation* approach.
[src:guava-java-lib/java-collections-framework] A bit field is less readable than an int enum constant.
[src:guava-java-lib/java-collections-framework] Also, if the elements are represented by bit fields, it is impossible to iterate through all of these elements.
[src:guava-java-lib/java-collections-framework] A recommended alternative approach is to use an `EnumSet`, where an int enum is used instead of a *bit field*.
[src:guava-java-lib/java-collections-framework] This approach uses an `EnumSet` to represent the set of values that belong to the same `Enum` type.
[src:guava-java-lib/java-collections-framework] Since the `EnumSet` implements the `Set` interface and no longer requires the use of bit-wise operations, this approach is more type-safe.
[src:guava-java-lib/java-collections-framework] Furthermore, there are many static factories that allow for object instantiation, such as the method `EnumSet.of()` method.
[src:guava-java-lib/java-collections-framework] After the introduction of the `EnumSet`, the *bit field representation* approach is considered to be obsolete.
[src:guava-java-lib/java-collections-framework] More specifically, it uses a **`java.util.LinkedHashMap`** to store the hashes and elements and to prevent duplicates.
[src:guava-java-lib/java-collections-framework] The `java.util.LinkedHashSet` class extends `HashSet` by creating a doubly linked list that links all of the elements by their insertion order.
[src:guava-java-lib/java-collections-framework] This ensures that the iteration order over the `Set` is predictable.
[src:guava-java-lib/java-collections-framework] `CopyOnWriteArraySet` is a concurrent replacement for a synchronized `Set`.
[src:guava-java-lib/java-collections-framework] It provides improved concurrency in many situations by removing the need to perform synchronization or making a copy of the object during iteration, similar to how `CopyOnWriteArrayList` acts as the concurrent replacement for a synchronized `List`.
[src:guava-java-lib/java-collections-framework] On the other hand, similar to `CopyOnWriteArrayList`, `CopyOnWriteArraySet` should not be used when synchronization is mandatory.
[src:guava-java-lib/java-collections-framework] The `java.util.SortedSet` interface extends the `java.util.Set` interface.
[src:guava-java-lib/java-collections-framework] Unlike a regular `Set`, the elements in a `SortedSet` are sorted, either by the element's `compareTo(T o)` method, or a method provided to the constructor of the `SortedSet`.
[src:guava-java-lib/java-collections-framework] The first and last elements of the `SortedSet` can be retrieved using the `first()` and `last()` methods respectively, and subsets can be created via minimum and maximum values, as well as beginning or ending at the beginning or ending of the `SortedSet`.
[src:guava-java-lib/java-collections-framework] The `java.util.TreeSet` class implements the `SortedSet` interface.
[src:guava-java-lib/java-collections-framework] The **`java.util.NavigableSet`** interface extends the `java.util.SortedSet` interface and has a few additional methods.
[src:guava-java-lib/java-collections-framework] The `floor(E e)`, `ceiling(E e)`, `lower(E e)`, and `higher(E e)` methods find an element in the set that's close to the parameter.
[src:guava-java-lib/java-collections-framework] Additionally, a descending iterator over the items in the `Set` is provided.
[src:guava-java-lib/java-collections-framework] As with `SortedSet`, `java.util.TreeSet` implements `NavigableSet`.
[src:guava-java-lib/java-collections-framework] `java.util.TreeSet` uses a red–black tree implemented by a **`java.util.TreeMap`**.
[src:guava-java-lib/java-collections-framework] The red–black tree ensures that there are no duplicates.
[src:guava-java-lib/java-collections-framework] Additionally, it allows `TreeSet` to implement **`java.util.SortedSet`**.
[src:guava-java-lib/java-collections-framework] `ConcurrentSkipListSet` acts as a concurrent replacement for implementations of a synchronized `SortedSet`.
[src:guava-java-lib/java-collections-framework] For example it replaces a `TreeSet` that has been wrapped by the `synchronizedMap` method.
[src:guava-java-lib/java-collections-framework] Maps are defined by the **`java.util.Map`** interface in Java.
[src:guava-java-lib/java-collections-framework] `Map`s are data structures that associate a key with an element.
[src:guava-java-lib/java-collections-framework] If the key is the hash code of the element, the `Map` is essentially a `Set`.
[src:guava-java-lib/java-collections-framework] If it's just an increasing number, it becomes a list.
[src:guava-java-lib/java-collections-framework] Examples of `Map` implementations include **`java.util.HashMap`**, **`java.util.LinkedHashMap`**, and **`java.util.TreeMap`**.
[src:guava-java-lib/java-collections-framework] `AbstractMap` is an example of a *skeletal implementation*.
[src:guava-java-lib/java-collections-framework] The direct subclasses of `AbstractMap` class include `ConcurrentSkipListMap`, `EnumMap`, `HashMap`, `IdentityHashMap`, `TreeMap` and `WeakHashMap`.
[src:guava-java-lib/java-collections-framework] `EnumMap` has comparable speed with an ordinal-indexed array.
[src:guava-java-lib/java-collections-framework] This is because `EnumMap` internally uses an array, with implementation details completely hidden from the developer.
[src:guava-java-lib/java-collections-framework] Hence, the EnumMap gets the type safety of a `Map` while the performance advantages of an array.
[src:guava-java-lib/java-collections-framework] The hashes of the keys are used to find the elements in various buckets.
[src:guava-java-lib/java-collections-framework] The `HashMap` is a hash-based collection.
[src:guava-java-lib/java-collections-framework] `LinkedHashMap` extends `HashMap` by creating a doubly linked list between the elements, allowing them to be accessed in the order in which they were inserted into the map.
[src:guava-java-lib/java-collections-framework] `LinkedHashMap` contains a `protected` `removeEldestEntry` method which is called by the `put` method whenever a new key is added to the `Map`.
[src:guava-java-lib/java-collections-framework] The `Map` removes its eldest entry whenever `removeEldestEntry` returns true.
[src:guava-java-lib/java-collections-framework] The `removeEldestEntry` method can be overridden.
[src:guava-java-lib/java-collections-framework] `TreeMap`, in contrast to `HashMap` and `LinkedHashMap`, uses a red–black tree.
[src:guava-java-lib/java-collections-framework] The keys are used as the values for the nodes in the tree, and the nodes point to the elements in the `Map`.
[src:guava-java-lib/java-collections-framework] `ConcurrentHashMap` is similar to `HashMap` and is also a hash-based collection.
[src:guava-java-lib/java-collections-framework] However, there are a number of differences, such as the differences in the locking strategy they use.
[src:guava-java-lib/java-collections-framework] The `ConcurrentHashMap` uses a completely different locking strategy to provide improved scalability and concurrency.
[src:guava-java-lib/java-collections-framework] `ConcurrentHashMap` does not synchronize every method using the same lock.
[src:guava-java-lib/java-collections-framework] Instead, `ConcurrentHashMap` use a mechanism known as *lock striping*.
[src:guava-java-lib/java-collections-framework] This mechanism provides a finer-grained locking mechanism.
[src:guava-java-lib/java-collections-framework] It also permits a higher degree of shared access.
[src:guava-java-lib/java-collections-framework] `ConcurrentSkipListMap` acts as a concurrent replacement for implementations of a synchronized `SortedMap`.
[src:guava-java-lib/java-collections-framework] `ConcurrentSkipListMap` is very similar to `ConcurrentSkipListSet`, since `ConcurrentSkipListMap` replaces a `TreeMap` that has been wrapped by the `synchronizedMap` method.
[src:guava-java-lib/java-collections-framework] The **`java.util.SortedMap`** interface extends the `java.util.Map` interface.
[src:guava-java-lib/java-collections-framework] This interface defines a `Map` that's sorted by the keys provided.
[src:guava-java-lib/java-collections-framework] Using, once again, the `compareTo()` method or a method provided in the constructor to the `SortedMap`, the key-element pairs are sorted by the keys.
[src:guava-java-lib/java-collections-framework] The first and last keys in the `Map` can be called by using the `firstKey()` and `lastKey()` methods respectively.
[src:guava-java-lib/java-collections-framework] Additionally, submaps can be created from minimum and maximum keys by using the `K) subMap(K fromKey, K toKey)` method.
[src:guava-java-lib/java-collections-framework] `SortedMap` is implemented by `java.util.TreeMap`.
[src:guava-java-lib/java-collections-framework] The **`java.util.NavigableMap`** interface extends `java.util.SortedMap` in various ways.
[src:guava-java-lib/java-collections-framework] Methods can be called that find the key or map entry that's closest to the given key in either direction.
[src:guava-java-lib/java-collections-framework] The map can also be reversed, and an iterator in reverse order can be generated from it.
[src:guava-java-lib/java-collections-framework] It's implemented by `java.util.TreeMap`.
[src:guava-java-lib/java-collections-framework] The **`java.util.concurrent.ConcurrentMap`** interface extends the `java.util.Map` interface.
[src:guava-java-lib/java-collections-framework] This interface a thread Safe `Map` interface, introduced as of Java programming language's Java Collections Framework version 1.5.
